{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627549"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:49:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:49:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17123"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17123"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0,0.12,0.1,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68652"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9813"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54109"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5032"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"},{"type":"tags","id":"9853"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23022"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68652"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman with chronic stable angina is prescribed ivabradine because she cannot tolerate beta blockers. Her heart rate is 85 beats per minute and blood pressure is 135/85 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of ivabradine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits the sodium-potassium ATPase pump","Blocks beta-adrenergic receptors","Blocks potassium channels in cardiac myocytes","Blocks calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle","Inhibits the funny current in sinoatrial node cells"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIvabradine works by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting the funny current (If) in sinoatrial node cells\u003C/strong\u003E. This reduces the rate of spontaneous depolarisation in pacemaker cells, leading to a decreased heart rate without affecting other cardiovascular parameters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting the sodium-potassium ATPase pump\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of digoxin, which increases intracellular calcium and affects cardiac contractility.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking beta-adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of beta blockers, which affect heart rate, contractility and blood pressure through antagonism of sympathetic stimulation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking potassium channels in cardiac myocytes\u003C/strong\u003E would affect cardiac repolarisation and potentially cause dangerous arrhythmias rather than simply reducing heart rate.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of calcium channel blockers, which reduce both heart rate and blood pressure through effects on multiple tissues.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe selective nature of ivabradine\u0027s action on the funny current makes it useful in patients who need heart rate reduction but cannot tolerate beta blockers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ivabradine selectively inhibits the funny current (If) in sinoatrial node cells to reduce heart rate.","Ivabradine does not affect blood pressure, contractility, or conduction through the atrioventricular node.","The funny current is a mixed sodium-potassium inward current that contributes to spontaneous depolarisation in pacemaker cells."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54109"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17123"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54109"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:04:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:05:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9813"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68652"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying a